  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "DG",
    "text": "This picture was taken in 1944. I was about 19 years old. It was taken in Ostrog. That was the time when I was all alone living with Stepaniuk, Mrs. Stepaniuk [PAUSES FOR 6 SECONDS] These are a few mementos that I was able to save from the war. This pocket book was given to me when I was 13 years old by my parents, and this was my talisman. And I carried it through the entire war, and I never parted with that. The-- the coin is ghetto money, and it's not from our ghetto. This comes from a-- I was able to obtain in Germany after the war. A feather that I found while I was living in the woods, and I thought it was so pretty. And I was hoping at the time, if I survive the war, I'd like to save the feather. The-- on the left there is the soap made out of Jewish fat. And it says [NON-ENGLISH], RIF. I was able to get this in Germany. Then I have a watch that my husband was wearing through the entire war, and some thread from home, and [PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS] brow-- eyebrow tweezer, eyebrow tweezer, and a snap.",
